{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478246"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17204"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17204"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.08,0.82,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1383"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8904"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10775"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent who noticed a white reflection in his right eye when taking flash photographs. The parent also reports that the child\u0027s right eye appears to drift outward occasionally. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. There is no family history of eye problems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an obvious white reflex in the right pupil. The left pupil appears normal. There is intermittent exotropia of the right eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diagnosis of retinoblastoma is confirmed on ophthalmology assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following genes is most likely to be mutated in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["BRCA1","TP53","RB1","APC","BRAF"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of retinoblastoma - leukocoria (white pupillary reflex) and strabismus. The genetic basis of retinoblastoma involves mutations in the \u003Cstrong\u003ERB1\u003C/strong\u003E tumour suppressor gene, located on chromosome 13q14. This was the first tumour suppressor gene to be identified and led to Knudson\u0027s two-hit hypothesis of cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are associated with hereditary breast and ovarian cancer syndrome. While it is also a tumour suppressor gene, it is not implicated in the development of retinoblastoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETP53\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause Li-Fraumeni syndrome and are associated with various cancers including sarcomas, breast cancer, and brain tumours, but not typically retinoblastoma. However, secondary mutations in TP53 can occur in advanced retinoblastoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAPC\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) and are associated with colorectal cancer. This gene is not involved in retinoblastoma pathogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRAF\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are commonly found in melanoma and some thyroid cancers, but are not associated with retinoblastoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn hereditary retinoblastoma (40% of cases), patients inherit one mutated copy of RB1 and acquire a second mutation in somatic cells (Knudson\u0027s two-hit hypothesis). These patients typically present with bilateral disease and are at risk of other cancers. In sporadic cases (60%), both RB1 mutations occur in somatic cells, usually resulting in unilateral disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinoblastoma is caused by mutations in the RB1 tumour suppressor gene","Hereditary retinoblastoma typically presents with bilateral disease and requires genetic counselling","Loss of both copies of RB1 is necessary for retinoblastoma development (two-hit hypothesis)"],"references":["Shields CL, Bas Z, Laiton A, Silva AMV, Sheikh A, Lally SE, et al. Retinoblastoma: emerging concepts in genetics, global disease burden, chemotherapy outcomes, and psychological impact. Eye. 2023 Apr;37(5):815\u201322."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17204"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T21:01:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T21:04:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9894"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69378"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links"